arch:property.oc:show_val: >4mm, 100% sorted FAST TRACKED> IGNORE ALL BUT THE FLOT A well-preserved unit full of large fragments and large animals. The bones are in very good condition and many of the articular surfaces suggest that the bones were articulated in the ground. The fragment size is larger than average with more than 70% over 4 cm and perhaps 10% over 10 cm. Edges are generally sharp with a little smoothing in some cases. There is a little gnawing and no trampling. Less than 3% of the bone is burnt, most of it carbonized. The scrap is equally divided between cattle-size and sheep-size long bone and ribs. For each size class about 20% of the scrap is ribs and the rest long bone. There are a small number of sheep size vertebrae. Cattle and sheep/goat are almost equally present among the diagnostics. There is also a reasonable amount of equid as well as a pig ulna and one small fragment of antler. Sheep/goat are present throughout the body, although the foot carpals/tarsals and phalanges are very underrepresented. Cattle are represented by teeth and feet as well as by fore limb fragments. There are many large cattle long bone fragments that are less than 1/2 the circumference and therefore not speciated. Both the cattle and the sheep foot bones have indications that they were at least partially articulated in the ground, wth now missing bones. The equid scapula has a healed fracture and one of the goat ulnae also seems to have a healed joint dislocation. This is a meaty, relatively unprocessed (by Catal standards) deposit. The condition of the bone suggests rapid burial and no redeposition. The spread of species is unusual in a small unit as is the high percentage of medium and large animals. However, the latter may be partly due to poor sieving - since the articular surfaces demonstrate that many small carpals and tarsals that were in the ground were not collected. Even allowing for that, the context is strongly post-consumption, with an unusual concentration on large, probably wild aniamls. The material was buried rapidly and not redeposited. There are two bird bones and two tools in the unit. There is one very fresh fragment of human bone that looks like it comes from a grave. The flot sample is moderately dense, clean -ooking fill. Less than 5% is burnt, most of it at low temperatures. There is a moderate amount of rolling/abrasion, although much of it may be modern; no trampling and little digestion. The scrap is all long bone, most of it is sheep size, but some of it larger. The identifiable bones are the small fragments of sheep/goat teeth and feet found in alll fill. There is one bird bone. The fill looks like it was not disturbed much, certainly not a surface. Last Number=F101

arch:string.div: The unique identifier for each contextual unit, matching those used in the central Çatalhöyük excavation database and in publications. The excavation uses single-context recording.
